sec.p:
Thermoelectric materials provide a great opportunity for direct conversion of heat to electricity and vice versa, that can be employed for a wide range of applications1–3. The efficiency of thermoelectric materials is described by the dimensionless figure of merit (ZT), that depends on a number of variables: Seebeck coefficient (thermopower, S), electric conductance (G), electronic thermal conductance (κel\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\kappa _{\mathrm{el}}$$\end{document}), and phononic thermal conductance (κph\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\kappa _{\mathrm{ph}}$$\end{document}), as follows4:1ZT=S2TGκel+κph,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} ZT = \frac{S^2 T G}{\kappa _{\mathrm{el}} + \kappa _{\mathrm{ph}}}, \end{aligned}$$\end{document}where T is the absolute temperature. When the phononic thermal transport vanishes, i.e. κph→0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
